{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476836"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:52:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:52:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13955"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13955"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.66,0.04,0.02,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50200"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6585"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13955"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35470"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1631"},{"type":"tags","id":"2578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13288"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16201"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50200"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-day-old neonate is reviewed on the postnatal ward. The baby was born at term via normal vaginal delivery and has been feeding well. The parents report noticing a rash that appeared yesterday. The baby has no significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the neonate appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple erythematous macules and papules, some with central pustules, scattered over the trunk, arms, and legs. The lesions are 2-3 mm in diameter and blanch with pressure. The rash spares the palms and soles. A Gram stain of the pustule contents reveals numerous eosinophils. Bacterial culture of the pustule contents shows no growth after 48 hours.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions best explains these clinical and laboratory findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Miliaria rubra","Erythema toxicum neonatorum","Staphylococcal impetigo","Candidiasis","Neonatal acne"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eerythema toxicum neonatorum\u003C/strong\u003E (ETN). This is a common, benign rash that affects up to 50% of term newborns. It typically appears within the first few days of life and resolves spontaneously within a week. The rash is characterised by erythematous macules, papules, or pustules that can occur anywhere on the body except the palms and soles. The Gram stain showing eosinophils and the negative culture are classic findings in ETN, though in practice this is a diagnosis that can often be made clinically without the need for diagnostics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeonatal acne\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with comedones and inflammatory papules and pustules, primarily on the face. It usually appears after the first few weeks of life and would not show eosinophils on Gram stain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMiliaria rubra\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as heat rash, presents with small, red, papules or vesicles due to obstruction of sweat ducts. It\u0027s more common in hot, humid environments and would not show eosinophils on Gram stain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcal impetigo\u003C/strong\u003E in neonates presents with pustules that rupture easily and form honey-coloured crusts. It would show gram-positive cocci on Gram stain and positive culture for \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECandidiasis\u003C/strong\u003E in neonates typically presents as oral thrush or nappy dermatitis. A generalised rash would be unusual, and Gram stain would show yeast forms rather than eosinophils.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erythema toxicum neonatorum is a common, benign neonatal rash characterised by erythematous macules, papules, or pustules.","The rash of erythema toxicum neonatorum typically appears within the first few days of life and resolves spontaneously within a week.","Gram stain of erythema toxicum neonatorum lesions shows eosinophils, and cultures are typically negative."],"references":["Roberts I. Nelson\u2019s textbook of pediatrics (20th edn.), by Kliegman R, Stanton B, St. Geme J, Schor N (eds). 2017:1364\u20131365 (2017). Available at: https://doi.org/10.1007/s00247-017-3907-9","Purvis D. Toxic erythema of the newborn. In: DermNet NZ [Online]. 2011. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/toxic-erythema-of-the-newborn","O\u0027Connor NR, McLaughlin MR, Ham P. Newborn skin: Part I. Common rashes. Am Fam Physician. 2008 Jan 1;77(1):47-52. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2008/0101/p47.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35470"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13955"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35470"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-08T10:42:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-08T10:42:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6585"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50200"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/ta